habitat_description:
All Regions:
Great gray owls utilize the same habitat year-round. In the U.S., this habitat includes deciduous or coniferous forests, up to 2,800 meters in elevation (Bull and Duncan 1993). Tree species include pine, spruce, paper birch, and poplar. The great gray owl can also be found in areas near water, boreal forests and spruce-tamarack bogs (in the northern portions of its range), and montane coniferous forest and meadows (NatureServe 2009). 

Northwest:
In California, breeding great gray owls prefer pine and fir forests between 750 and 2,250 meters, especially those adjacent to meadows. In central Oregon, habitat includes meadow systems associtated with coniferous forests. In northeastern Oregon, all forest types were utilized, although 50 percent of nests were found in fir forests.  In Idaho and Wyoming, most great gray owls were sighted in the lodgepole pine/Douglas-fir/aspen zone (Bull and Duncan 1993). C. Maynard, 9feb10.
